Initialize a bare repository:
git init --bare ~/.dotfiles

Create a shell alias to interact with it:
alias dotfiles='git --git-dir=$HOME/.dotfiles/ --work-tree=$HOME'

Add the alias to your shell config (e.g., ~/.zshrc or ~/.bashrc) and reload it.
Configure Git to hide untracked files:
dotfiles config status.showUntrackedFiles no

Track files using dotfiles add .bashrc and commit normally.
   
dotfiles add .bashrc .config/nvim/init.lua
dotfiles commit -m "Initial commit"
dotfiles status

Push to a remote
dotfiles remote add origin git@github.com:username/dotfiles.git
dotfiles push -u origin main

Set up on a new machine:
git clone --bare https://github.com/username/dotfiles.git ~/.dotfiles
alias dotfiles='git --git-dir=$HOME/.dotfiles/ --work-tree=$HOME'
dotfiles checkout
dotfiles config status.showUntrackedFiles no

Note: If you have existing files, use dotfiles checkout -f to overwrite

